---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import FAQ from '../../components/FAQ.astro';
import { localizedPath } from '../../i18n/utils';

const locale = 'en';
const faq = [
  {
    question: 'What counts as commuting cost?',
    answer:
      'Three layers: direct transport costs (transit pass, fuel, parking, tolls), time cost (one-way minutes × 2 × workdays × your personal price of time), and invisible wear (vehicle depreciation and maintenance, fatigue, attention). Most people only count the first layer — usually the smallest of the three.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I value commute time at my full hourly wage?',
    answer:
      'No — commute time saved rarely converts into paid hours. A more honest approach: ask what you would genuinely pay to buy back one hour of after-work time. For most people that lands at 25%–50% of their wage. Use that self-set price and your conclusion will survive scrutiny.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do I judge a cheaper apartment that is farther away?',
    answer:
      'Subtract the added monthly commute cost (transport + time × your time price) from the monthly rent saved. Plenty of "$300 cheaper" apartments turn negative once 70 extra daily minutes enter the math. The commute cost calculator runs the comparison in a minute.',
  },
  {
    question: 'My train commute lets me read or listen to podcasts — still a cost?',
    answer:
      'Recoverable commute time (seated, no need to watch the road) can reasonably be discounted — say, by half. Driving and riding time is nearly unrecoverable since attention stays on traffic. Estimate the two kinds separately instead of applying one flat discount.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does this apply to buying a home?',
    answer:
      'Even more so — a bad rental commute can be fixed by moving; a mortgage commute is a ten-year commitment. Multiply the monthly gap by 120 before deciding. For the rent-versus-buy question itself, see the rent vs buy guide.',
  },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="The True Cost of Commuting: Does the Cheaper Rent Actually Pay for It?"
  description="Rent drops $300, the commute grows by 70 minutes a day — good trade? A three-layer commute costing method (transport, priced time, invisible wear) with a breakeven comparison and a free calculator."
  locale={locale}
  updated="2026-07-17"
>
  <p>
    &ldquo;Move one town over and the same apartment is $300 cheaper!&rdquo;
    Every renter&rsquo;s ears perk up. The full sentence, though, is:
    &ldquo;$300 cheaper, and 70 more minutes on the road every day.&rdquo;
    What the second half costs, most people never compute — it never appears
    on any bill. Here is a three-layer method, and at the end you can run
    your own numbers through the free
    <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/tools/commute-cost')}>commute cost calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Layer one: direct transport costs — the visible part</h2>
  <p>
    Transit pass, fuel, parking, tolls. Easiest to compute, and most often
    mistaken for the whole answer. Two commonly missed items:
    <strong>vehicle depreciation</strong> — every mile wears the car whether
    or not you notice at the pump — and the bad-weather backup plan
    (occasional ride-hailing when the usual mode fails). For car commuters,
    all-in per-mile cost typically runs two to three times the fuel-only
    number.
  </p>

  <h2>Layer two: time — the real heavyweight</h2>
  <p>
    Seventy extra minutes a day across 22 workdays is 25.7 hours a month —
    the equivalent of three extra unpaid workdays. The key move is pricing
    that time honestly:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Not at your full wage.</strong> Saved commute time mostly
      becomes rest, chores, and family time — not billable hours. Full-wage
      pricing systematically overstates the loss.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>At your buy-back price.</strong> What would you actually pay
      to get one hour of evening back? Honest answers usually land at
      25%–50% of the hourly wage. At a $30 wage with a $10 buy-back price:
      25.7 hours × $10 = $257 a month of time cost.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Discount recoverable time.</strong> A seated train ride with a
      book can fairly take a further 50% discount. Driving takes none —
      attention belongs to the road the whole way.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Now run the duel: added cost versus saved rent</h2>
  <p>
    Continuing the example: $300 of rent saved; against it, $60 of extra
    transport plus $257 of time cost = $317. The trade is already slightly
    negative at a $10 time price — and it gets worse the more you value your
    evenings. At a $15 buy-back price the &ldquo;cheaper&rdquo; apartment
    loses by more than $100 a month.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is the real nature of the commute decision: <strong>it is not an
    objective &ldquo;which is cheaper&rdquo; question but a subjective
    &ldquo;what is your hour worth&rdquo; question</strong> — with an
    objective part that still has to be computed correctly. The
    <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/tools/commute-cost')}>calculator</a>
    takes transport costs and your time price separately, so two scenarios
    can sit side by side.
  </p>

  <h2>Layer three: invisible wear — outside the formula, inside the decision</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Compounding fatigue.</strong> Commutes over 60 minutes each way correlate consistently with worse sleep and less exercise — costs that bill you months later as &ldquo;always tired.&rdquo;</li>
    <li><strong>Lost flexibility.</strong> Living far turns overtime, dinners, and the last train into stress events; &ldquo;it&rsquo;s a long way back anyway&rdquo; quietly reshapes your social life.</li>
    <li><strong>Risk exposure.</strong> Doubling motorcycle or car miles doubles accident exposure — a real cost beyond the insurance premium.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This layer resists precise pricing; use it as a tiebreaker. If layers one
    and two say the move wins by a small margin, layer three usually flips
    it. Only a decisive win deserves the moving truck.
  </p>

  <h2>Three verdicts</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Rent savings clearly beat total commute cost →</strong> move — but verify with a real-week test: actual door-to-door time runs 15–20% over the map estimate once waiting and transfers count.</li>
    <li><strong>Roughly even →</strong> don&rsquo;t. Moving itself costs money (deposits, movers, settling in) that a thin margin never repays.</li>
    <li><strong>Buying a home →</strong> multiply the monthly gap by 120 and look again. The commute is the one variable you cannot renovate. For the ownership question itself, see the <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/rent-vs-buy-guide')}>rent vs buy guide</a> or run the <a href={localizedPath(locale, '/tools/rent-vs-buy')}>rent vs buy calculator</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <FAQ items={faq} />

  <p class="privacy-note">
    Privacy note: the commute cost calculator runs entirely in your browser —
    wage and cost figures you enter are never uploaded to any server. This
    article describes a general estimation method and is not financial
    advice; actual fares, fuel prices, and rents vary by location.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>
